WEBVTT

00:00:10.270 --> 00:00:13.470
Welcome everyone to the
Mac OS X Server Overview session.

00:00:13.520 --> 00:00:17.180
So we have a lot of stuff to
cover today in Mac OS X Server.

00:00:17.180 --> 00:00:20.780
We're going to go deep into some of
the stuff that's new in Leopard Server.

00:00:20.780 --> 00:00:22.580
And we've been working
on this for a while,

00:00:22.580 --> 00:00:25.240
and so we're really excited
to be able to share with you,

00:00:25.240 --> 00:00:28.050
to have you guys all here,
and to be able to talk about the

00:00:28.050 --> 00:00:30.000
new features of Leopard Server.

00:00:30.830 --> 00:00:33.250
Those of you who have been using
the product for a while know

00:00:33.250 --> 00:00:36.230
that we've stayed consistent to a
strategy that we've had throughout

00:00:36.230 --> 00:00:37.860
the development of Mac OS X Server.

00:00:37.920 --> 00:00:41.250
We've taken an industry
standard Unix operating system,

00:00:41.300 --> 00:00:44.870
we've picked from among the best open
source packages that are available,

00:00:44.870 --> 00:00:47.160
and we've tied them together,
integrated them to make sure that

00:00:47.210 --> 00:00:51.080
they all work together and tie them
together with Apple ease of use.

00:00:51.640 --> 00:00:55.480
It's been over five years now that
we've been releasing Mac OS X Server.

00:00:55.480 --> 00:00:59.690
And from the beginning back
into 2001 all the way up to now,

00:00:59.730 --> 00:01:01.700
we're on our seventh release.

00:01:01.800 --> 00:01:04.030
Actually, we have two new releases today.

00:01:04.110 --> 00:01:07.610
The first, Tiger Server on Intel,
or Tiger Server Universal,

00:01:07.760 --> 00:01:12.900
is a port of the existing
Tiger Server onto the Intel hardware.

00:01:13.010 --> 00:01:16.970
So Mac OS X Server now runs
on Intel and supports the new

00:01:16.970 --> 00:01:19.320
Mac Pro and XServe hardware.

00:01:19.330 --> 00:01:22.470
But we're going to spend the bulk
of this presentation talking about

00:01:22.470 --> 00:01:24.600
what's new in Leopard Server.

00:01:24.630 --> 00:01:27.440
And for the next hour,
we're going to go into

00:01:27.440 --> 00:01:29.220
detail about four areas.

00:01:29.370 --> 00:01:32.220
We're going to talk about the
server foundations and improvements

00:01:32.220 --> 00:01:34.800
we've made in the server,
as well as improvements to the

00:01:34.800 --> 00:01:37.390
services and some new services as well.

00:01:37.480 --> 00:01:40.640
We're going to talk about streamlined
server setup and how we've improved

00:01:40.640 --> 00:01:42.140
the management of the server.

00:01:42.180 --> 00:01:44.150
We have our new iCal Calendaring Server.

00:01:44.400 --> 00:01:47.300
And we're going to talk about Teams,
which is a new wiki and a set of

00:01:47.300 --> 00:01:49.040
web services in Leopard Server.

00:01:49.320 --> 00:01:52.620
So to start with,
and to talk about server foundations,

00:01:52.630 --> 00:01:55.320
I'd like to welcome to the stage,
Kazu Yanagihara.

00:01:55.420 --> 00:01:57.960
He's our senior engineering
manager for Leopard Server.

00:01:57.960 --> 00:01:58.960
Kazu?

00:02:00.670 --> 00:02:02.510
Thanks, Greg.

00:02:04.430 --> 00:02:05.220
Good afternoon.

00:02:05.310 --> 00:02:06.740
It's nice to see you all again.

00:02:06.740 --> 00:02:08.930
See you just once a year.

00:02:08.980 --> 00:02:12.490
So let's start with the base OS.

00:02:12.590 --> 00:02:14.540
For those of you who are
new to Mac OS X Server,

00:02:14.540 --> 00:02:18.280
it's based on the solid foundation
provided by Mac Chrono and BSD.

00:02:18.280 --> 00:02:22.160
It offers all the key features
that are expected in modern OS,

00:02:22.160 --> 00:02:25.400
such as protected memory,
unified buffer cache,

00:02:25.400 --> 00:02:29.760
journaled file system, link aggregation,
and on and on and on.

00:02:30.760 --> 00:02:34.110
It's also fully Unix compliant,
so it's really easy to port software

00:02:34.270 --> 00:02:37.290
from other Unix platforms to ours.

00:02:37.740 --> 00:02:39.250
And we now have 64-bit.

00:02:39.400 --> 00:02:42.970
As Simon Patient mentioned earlier,
we are now fully, fully 64-bit,

00:02:42.970 --> 00:02:48.240
support 64-bit on both
PowerPC and Intel platforms.

00:02:48.380 --> 00:02:51.140
Everything from the low-level
libraries all the way up to GUI.

00:02:51.360 --> 00:02:53.950
And some of our services,
such as QuickTime Streaming

00:02:53.950 --> 00:02:57.320
Server and MySQL,
can be ported to 64-bit so they can

00:02:57.320 --> 00:03:00.090
take advantage of the large data set.

00:03:00.370 --> 00:03:04.620
Also on the Leopard platform,
the 32-bit applications run natively

00:03:04.620 --> 00:03:07.300
side-by-side with 64-bit apps.

00:03:07.300 --> 00:03:10.300
So there's no emulation mode and
there's no performance penalty.

00:03:12.700 --> 00:03:15.250
Let's talk about Open Directory,
which is Apple's directory

00:03:15.320 --> 00:03:16.700
and authentication system.

00:03:16.700 --> 00:03:24.650
The directory portion is based
on the industry standard LDAP,

00:03:24.650 --> 00:03:29.400
and Corvus is our primary
authentication mechanism,

00:03:29.400 --> 00:03:29.400
although we do support a
large number of legacy methods

00:03:29.400 --> 00:03:29.400
such as APOP and Chrome MD5.

00:03:29.710 --> 00:03:33.060
The audio really also fits really
nicely with other directories such as

00:03:33.060 --> 00:03:38.040
Active Directory or NIS or Fluff BIOS.

00:03:38.040 --> 00:03:38.040
Excuse me.

00:03:38.260 --> 00:03:39.960
And lastly, we support replication.

00:03:40.080 --> 00:03:43.100
So if you need to have the large
deployment of open directory,

00:03:43.100 --> 00:03:43.800
you have that.

00:03:43.820 --> 00:03:47.790
You can have up to 64
replicas right now on Tiger.

00:03:49.100 --> 00:03:53.000
And this is what's new in Open Directory,
or some of them.

00:03:53.000 --> 00:03:55.690
First, we have support for
cross-domain authorization in

00:03:55.690 --> 00:03:57.590
addition to authentication.

00:03:57.800 --> 00:04:00.950
We also have RADIUS integrated
into Open Directory now.

00:04:00.960 --> 00:04:03.070
Thank you.

00:04:04.910 --> 00:04:07.400
And it's based on free,
ready-to-open-source projects.

00:04:07.400 --> 00:04:09.850
So if you have a bunch of
airport base stations to manage,

00:04:10.020 --> 00:04:14.740
you can do so now in a centralized manner
using open directory users and groups.

00:04:14.820 --> 00:04:17.250
And lastly,
we now have cascading replication

00:04:17.320 --> 00:04:19.280
or the multi-tier replication.

00:04:19.330 --> 00:04:22.120
So you will no longer have the 64 limit,
and you can have hundreds and

00:04:22.150 --> 00:04:26.230
hundreds of replicas if you have
large deployment of open directory.

00:04:26.530 --> 00:04:29.540
So that's a few of the
new features in Leopard.

00:04:29.660 --> 00:04:32.630
And if you're interested in this topic,
we've got a lot more to talk about,

00:04:32.710 --> 00:04:37.720
so there's a session dedicated to
it at 2:00 tomorrow in this room.

00:04:38.630 --> 00:04:41.200
And actually, that's all I had for the
foundation portion since we got

00:04:41.200 --> 00:04:42.360
a lot of new stuff to talk about.

00:04:42.360 --> 00:04:45.060
So let's jump right into the services.

00:04:46.100 --> 00:04:48.700
As Greg mentioned earlier,
we have lots and lots of services,

00:04:48.700 --> 00:04:50.840
and we seem to be adding
new services every year.

00:04:51.220 --> 00:04:54.380
And we have more than a few
to add this year as well.

00:04:54.900 --> 00:04:57.480
And most of them are based
on open source projects,

00:04:57.480 --> 00:05:00.310
and then many of those that we
develop are also open source,

00:05:00.360 --> 00:05:04.580
