the existing services and some of

00:05:09.210 --> 00:05:11.640
the enhancements we made to them.

00:05:11.640 --> 00:05:13.700
And let's start with mail.

00:05:13.740 --> 00:05:17.260
So interesting one is
the group mailing list.

00:05:17.290 --> 00:05:21.260
Now you can simply send email
to any open directory group,

00:05:21.260 --> 00:05:24.620
and behind the scene,
the mail server does the

00:05:24.620 --> 00:05:28.470
old configuration for you,
and all the members of the

00:05:28.540 --> 00:05:31.170
group receive the email,
so you no longer have to create a

00:05:31.170 --> 00:05:31.170
separate mailing list configuration.

00:05:31.450 --> 00:05:34.650
Another big ticket item is
the Active-Active clustering

00:05:34.650 --> 00:05:36.220
using XAN as a backend.

00:05:36.220 --> 00:05:39.930
You cannot do it with NFS because
we rely on some locking semantics

00:05:39.930 --> 00:05:44.190
that's supported by XAN,
but this should really help people deploy

00:05:44.520 --> 00:05:50.040
much wider deployment of our mail server
as well as high availability solution.

00:05:50.040 --> 00:05:54.560
Also got the vacation messages
as well as 64-bit mail services.

00:05:55.780 --> 00:06:00.370
iChat Server is now based on Java 2,
which has a brand new code base.

00:06:00.460 --> 00:06:05.080
And it's also fully XMPP compliant,
so you can now federate with

00:06:05.080 --> 00:06:08.640
any XMPP servers out there,
including Google Talk.

00:06:08.740 --> 00:06:11.340
And we want to make sure that
any communication that you

00:06:11.400 --> 00:06:15.050
have between servers is secure,
even over the public internet.

00:06:15.110 --> 00:06:20.400
So we now support certificate-based
encryption as well between servers.

00:06:20.810 --> 00:06:24.590
And one of the most requested features
for iChart Server from the previous

00:06:24.590 --> 00:06:28.060
release was the chart archiving,
where every single message that

00:06:28.060 --> 00:06:31.100
passes through the server gets
saved and archived so you can

00:06:31.100 --> 00:06:33.000
search and retrieve them later.

00:06:33.130 --> 00:06:38.870
So this is really important to a lot of
companies out there for legal reasons,

00:06:38.870 --> 00:06:38.870
so we have that in the product now.

00:06:39.190 --> 00:06:42.540
And last but not least,
we do have Kerberos support for both

00:06:42.540 --> 00:06:46.100
iChat Server and iChat Client in Leopard.

00:06:46.100 --> 00:06:48.980
Which means if you are
binding to Active Directory,

00:06:49.180 --> 00:06:52.100
you no longer have to pass
Createx Pass over the network.

00:06:52.470 --> 00:06:55.090
So that's iChat Server.

00:06:55.330 --> 00:06:57.910
Let's move on to the web front.

00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:01.320
So now we promoted Apache 2
to the first-class citizens,

00:07:01.440 --> 00:07:04.580
so you get to choose which
version of Apache you want to use.

00:07:04.600 --> 00:07:08.580
And it depends on what you choose,
we automatically configure things behind.

00:07:08.580 --> 00:07:12.780
For example, if you select Apache 2,
we automatically configure PHP 4,

00:07:12.810 --> 00:07:16.940
or if you have Apache 2, PHP 5.

00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:19.820
And also, you can use our admin
GUI with ease of version,

00:07:19.960 --> 00:07:22.980
so you get to pick,
and you can basically do

00:07:22.980 --> 00:07:24.820
anything you want with it.

00:07:24.830 --> 00:07:28.690
We are also including Ruby on
Rails with Mongrel in this release

00:07:28.690 --> 00:07:31.000
for your rapid development pleasure.

00:07:31.000 --> 00:07:38.720
But we also include ModFastCGI,
so if you want to, you can use Ruby on

00:07:38.720 --> 00:07:40.610
Rails with Apache as well.

00:07:40.660 --> 00:07:42.680
You have the choice there.

00:07:42.830 --> 00:07:46.100
Both JBoss and Tomcats
get the version upgrade,

00:07:46.100 --> 00:07:49.410
and both Apache 2 and MySQL are 64-bit.

00:07:49.450 --> 00:07:53.100
The Apache 1 is going to
stay as a 32-bit server.

00:07:54.670 --> 00:07:56.560
And if you're interested
in this technology area,

00:07:56.560 --> 00:07:59.590
we have a separate session on Wednesday,
and we have a couple of cool demos,

00:07:59.710 --> 00:08:02.400
so hope you guys can make that.

00:08:04.100 --> 00:08:05.340
QTSS.

00:08:05.340 --> 00:08:08.800
So one of the most requested features,
mostly from the higher education,

00:08:08.810 --> 00:08:11.090
was support for open
directory integration.

00:08:11.210 --> 00:08:16.060
So we're working on that right now for
both authentication and access control.

00:08:16.080 --> 00:08:19.970
We're also working on 3GP version
6 support for improved quality

00:08:19.970 --> 00:08:24.090
of service on your streaming to
cell phones and handheld devices.

00:08:24.100 --> 00:08:27.580
And again,
the QTSS is also going to be 64-bit.

00:08:29.500 --> 00:08:31.040
Let's talk about X Grid 2.

00:08:31.040 --> 00:08:33.210
There are a couple of
interesting features here.

00:08:33.310 --> 00:08:37.320
Scoreboarding is a feature where
the individual agents can assign

00:08:37.320 --> 00:08:41.180
scores to themselves based on the
configuration and capabilities.

00:08:41.310 --> 00:08:44.680
For example, CPU speed,
the types of GPU it has,

00:08:44.680 --> 00:08:46.620
or even free disk space.

00:08:46.790 --> 00:08:49.430
And those scores get sent
back to the controller,

00:08:49.440 --> 00:08:52.300
and then the controller assigns
jobs to the agents that are most

00:08:52.300 --> 00:08:54.500
qualified based on the scoreboarding.

00:08:54.650 --> 00:08:57.670
So basically,
you can have a much smarter grid,

00:08:57.670 --> 00:09:01.300
and the end result is you
have faster job execution.

00:09:01.660 --> 00:09:05.890
The Grid Anyway API is a new API that
helps you make your application

00:09:05.920 --> 00:09:08.020
transparent when you use X Grid.

00:09:08.290 --> 00:09:10.880
What API does is takes the job
and checks to see if there's a

00:09:10.880 --> 00:09:14.200
grid available on the network,
and if there is, it distributes.

00:09:14.320 --> 00:09:17.740
But if there's not,
it simply just loops back

00:09:17.740 --> 00:09:21.770
and executes it locally,
which means the application

00:09:22.020 --> 00:09:26.990
doesn't have to have two separate
code paths to use X Grid now.

00:09:26.990 --> 00:09:31.590
And also supports directory-based
configuration now.

00:09:31.590 --> 00:09:32.190
And we do have a separate
session on Friday if you're

00:09:32.190 --> 00:09:32.190
interested in this topic.

00:09:34.420 --> 00:09:36.700
Managed Desktop gets a bunch
of new features as well.

00:09:36.700 --> 00:09:39.610
Got the nested group support,
application launch restrictions,

00:09:39.640 --> 00:09:41.890
and we now finally have
command line tools.

00:09:41.900 --> 00:09:45.590
So if you don't like the GUI,
you can do it from the

00:09:45.590 --> 00:09:47.480
command line as well.

00:09:48.610 --> 00:09:52.880
The external account is the feature where
you can take your home directory and

00:09:52.880 --> 00:09:55.800
then move it to your portable device,
FireWire drives,

00:09:55.860 --> 00:09:58.900
so you can carry your home
directory wherever you go.

