00:10:45.720 --> 00:10:48.290
So now let's talk about
some of the new ones,

00:10:48.370 --> 00:10:51.040
starting with Spotlight Server.

00:10:51.080 --> 00:10:53.930
So with Leopard,
you can search any network volumes

00:10:54.030 --> 00:10:57.030
that's mounted real transparently
as if it's a local volume.

00:10:57.210 --> 00:10:59.670
So all the new features of
Leopard is going to be supported,

00:10:59.670 --> 00:11:03.590
including recent items, Quick Look,
and so on.

00:11:03.760 --> 00:11:06.350
Access Control is enforced
and there's no configuration,

00:11:06.350 --> 00:11:09.360
so out of the box you can
simply mount any server volumes

00:11:09.360 --> 00:11:11.140
and you can do the search.

00:11:11.140 --> 00:11:14.790
The DVD you have supports
spotlight searching on AFP only,

00:11:14.910 --> 00:11:19.220
but before we ship we're
going to have support for SMB.

00:11:19.220 --> 00:11:21.660
We also have this Apache module
that lets you do spotlight

00:11:21.660 --> 00:11:24.640
searching from your web client,
so if you're interested you

00:11:24.720 --> 00:11:26.090
can take a look at that.

00:11:27.590 --> 00:11:30.240
And now let's talk
about Podcast Producer.

00:11:30.240 --> 00:11:32.960
What is it?

00:11:33.080 --> 00:11:37.430
It's a complete solution that lets
you create and publish podcasts.

00:11:37.480 --> 00:11:42.220
So let's think of an example,
university environment.

00:11:42.330 --> 00:11:45.560
What a lot of people want there is
really capture all the lecturers

00:11:45.560 --> 00:11:48.340
out there and make them available
as a podcast to everybody,

00:11:48.340 --> 00:11:51.340
all the students and
perhaps to the public.

00:11:51.420 --> 00:11:55.500
And Podcast Producer lets you do
that without having any manual steps.

00:11:55.500 --> 00:11:57.960
So let's take a look at how it works.

00:11:59.690 --> 00:12:02.680
So going back to the lecture example,
in the lecture hall,

00:12:02.680 --> 00:12:05.480
you probably have a camera
sitting in the back.

00:12:05.750 --> 00:12:07.850
And when the professor
walks into the lecture room,

00:12:07.930 --> 00:12:10.950
all he has to do is use our
new remote camera control

00:12:10.990 --> 00:12:13.760
software to start the camera.

00:12:14.350 --> 00:12:17.760
And you get to do that either via our
new Cocoa app or from using your browser.

00:12:17.760 --> 00:12:22.080
And then all those machines
that's connected to camera,

00:12:22.080 --> 00:12:23.880
we have this new video recorder software.

00:12:23.880 --> 00:12:27.030
And what it does is it takes
the raw input from the camera,

00:12:27.440 --> 00:12:30.740
converts it to H.264,
and then when the lecture is done,

00:12:30.780 --> 00:12:32.360
it uploads it to the server.

00:12:32.360 --> 00:12:36.030
And this podcast producer server,
it's sort of the brain of this

00:12:36.030 --> 00:12:38.760
whole system that coordinates
different activities and also

00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:40.740
does things like access control.

00:12:40.740 --> 00:12:42.760
So in this particular case,
when the file gets

00:12:42.880 --> 00:12:45.640
delivered to the server,
what it does is it tells

00:12:45.640 --> 00:12:49.700
the workflow engine to start
processing that movie file.

00:12:51.600 --> 00:12:55.070
And this workflow engine is just
simply a cluster of X Grid agents

00:12:55.180 --> 00:12:57.480
that's sharing the same shared volume.

00:12:57.600 --> 00:13:01.220
X, typically,
but it could be NFS as well.

00:13:01.500 --> 00:13:25.300
[Transcript missing]

00:13:25.880 --> 00:13:29.980
And when the whole processing is done,
what the server does is it tells the

00:13:29.980 --> 00:13:34.770
publishing servers that the output file
is ready for delivery to the end user.

00:13:34.840 --> 00:13:37.300
And typically for the podcast,
it's a weblog server,

00:13:37.300 --> 00:13:40.280
but you can also deliver via
a QuickTime streaming server.

00:13:40.330 --> 00:13:42.400
Maybe you have a high-res
version of the movie,

00:13:42.450 --> 00:13:44.550
so you can make it available
in two different ways,

00:13:44.550 --> 00:13:48.320
or even just post it to the web
server so you can do the web download.

00:13:48.880 --> 00:13:52.140
In addition, optionally,
you can also send an email notification

00:13:52.140 --> 00:13:55.900
to a set of users that you specify
with the URL inside so they know

00:13:55.990 --> 00:13:57.950
when something new comes in.

00:14:01.330 --> 00:14:05.260
So it's real complete end-to-end
solution that lets you capture,

00:14:05.310 --> 00:14:07.280
process, and deliver.

00:14:07.280 --> 00:14:10.800
And one thing to note there is the only
